02:56.844 --> 02:59.638
♪

03:03.266 --> 03:06.020
It is one of the great
pleasures of my life

03:06.061 --> 03:07.813
to join the river of people

03:07.855 --> 03:10.024
rushing through the streets.

03:28.667 --> 03:31.753
♪

03:42.305 --> 03:47.268
Vietnam, it grabs you
and doesn't let you go.

03:47.310 --> 03:50.480
Once you love it, you
love it forever.

03:52.315 --> 03:54.526
I've been coming
here since 2000,

03:54.568 --> 03:56.653
the first time I'd been in
this part of the world,

03:56.695 --> 03:58.906
and it's held a special
place in my heart

03:58.947 --> 04:02.159
and my imagination since.

04:02.201 --> 04:03.869
I keep coming back.

04:03.911 --> 04:05.286
I have to.

04:05.328 --> 04:08.498
♪

04:18.716 --> 04:21.344
Vietnam has changed since
last time I was here.

04:21.386 --> 04:23.180
It's changing every minute.

04:29.811 --> 04:34.691
But some things, for now
anyway, remain the same.

04:34.733 --> 04:38.195
Important things
like this stuff.

04:38.237 --> 04:39.988
That's gonna be good.

04:40.030 --> 04:42.199
Bun oc, first meal in Hanoi,

04:42.241 --> 04:43.972
and it's something they do here

04:43.973 --> 04:45.702
better than anywhere else.

04:45.744 --> 04:48.413
Okay, I'm officially
in Hanoi now.

04:51.041 --> 04:54.335
Mmm, magic.

04:54.377 --> 04:57.193
A spicy, wonderful broth
with tomatoes and herb

04:57.194 --> 04:59.591
and noodles and fresh snails.

04:59.633 --> 05:01.135
Plump and delicious.

05:01.176 --> 05:02.803
Look at those beauties.

05:02.844 --> 05:06.347
Come to me, plump,
little love muscle.

05:08.183 --> 05:09.434
Mmm.

05:11.394 --> 05:14.606
Hanoi, capital city of Vietnam.

05:14.648 --> 05:17.192
Seven and a half million
people live here.

05:17.234 --> 05:18.586
In the winter, it's
chilly and damp.

05:18.610 --> 05:22.363
In the summer, hot,
humid, subtropical.

05:22.405 --> 05:25.867
The boulevards and many of
the buildings are French.

05:27.035 --> 05:31.539
But its heart and soul is
always, always Vietnamese.

05:34.793 --> 05:37.838
Americans coming here as
tourists for the first time,

05:37.879 --> 05:39.380
especially veterans of the war,

05:39.422 --> 05:42.759
are shocked by how
friendly the place is.

05:42.801 --> 05:46.013
People are genuinely
happy to see you.

05:46.054 --> 05:47.764
♪

05:47.806 --> 05:51.143
This is Hanoi's Old Quarter,
but it's looking less

05:51.144 --> 05:52.435
and less old these days.

05:52.477 --> 05:54.771
Man, this area's changed though.

05:54.813 --> 05:58.775
I mean, the Irish/Czech-
themed pub next door?

05:58.817 --> 06:00.401
♪

06:00.443 --> 06:03.030
Vietnam is a young country.

06:03.071 --> 06:06.033
Almost half of Vietnamese
are under the age of 30.

06:06.074 --> 06:09.515
Fewer every year even
remember what they call here

06:09.516 --> 06:11.412
the American War.

06:13.623 --> 06:15.416
Those years were a defining time

06:15.458 --> 06:18.045
for just about everyone,
Vietnamese or American,

06:18.086 --> 06:19.420
who lived through them.

06:19.462 --> 06:21.006
And though there are still a lot

06:21.048 --> 06:23.529
of conflicted feelings back
home, for most Vietnamese

06:23.530 --> 06:27.221
these days, the war has
become an abstraction,

06:27.262 --> 06:28.889
not even a memory.

06:30.473 --> 06:32.600
Vietnam is still a poor nation,

06:32.642 --> 06:34.686
but the standard of
living has improved a lot

06:34.728 --> 06:37.168
with the relaxing of hardline

06:37.169 --> 06:39.607
communist economic policies.

06:39.649 --> 06:42.610
More and more foreign
tourists every year.

06:42.652 --> 06:46.447
Western chains inevitable
are everywhere.

06:46.489 --> 06:49.450
And President Obama is
visiting for the first time,

06:49.492 --> 06:52.246
taking another step
on the long path

06:52.287 --> 06:54.039
toward normalizing relations

06:54.081 --> 06:55.249
between the two countries.

06:55.290 --> 06:56.771
That is good.

06:56.772 --> 06:58.252
Ooh, hot.

06:58.293 --> 07:01.046
Ooh, I hit that chili hard.

07:28.531 --> 07:30.491
- Nice to meet you.
- Yes.

07:30.533 --> 07:32.369
- It's such a pleasure.

07:32.370 --> 07:34.371
- Oh, and we have -a
beer ready to go, great.

07:32.411 --> 07:34.371
- Yes.

07:34.413 --> 07:37.498
So we're doing by bottle,
or we're going to pour it

07:35.747 --> 07:37.498
in a glass?

07:37.540 --> 07:39.376
How would you do it
if I wasn't here?

07:39.418 --> 07:41.128
- I would pour it in the glass.
- Okay.

07:41.169 --> 07:43.547
In Vietnam, particularly
in the North, it would be

07:43.548 --> 07:45.506
very improper for
a woman to drink

07:45.548 --> 07:47.402
- straight from the bottle.
- Oh, really? Oh, really?

07:47.426 --> 07:49.510
- Yeah.
- Okay, well, I'm glad I know this now.

07:49.552 --> 07:50.511
Cheers.

07:50.553 --> 07:53.681
Thao is an Eisenhower Fellow
and a Fulbright scholar.

07:53.723 --> 07:56.351
She's devoted her career to
help strengthen the bonds

07:56.393 --> 07:58.519
between Vietnam and the US.

07:58.561 --> 08:01.106
Today, we drove to the
outskirts of Hanoi.

08:01.148 --> 08:02.336
- Uh-hmm?

08:02.337 --> 08:03.524
- Cranes, tall buildings.

08:03.566 --> 08:05.402
People moving from the
country to the city?

08:05.444 --> 08:06.570
- Uh-hmm?

08:06.571 --> 08:09.530
- Marc Jacobs, Prada,
I mean, this is

08:07.737 --> 08:09.530
a very young country now.

08:09.572 --> 08:11.408
Oh, very much a young nation.

08:11.450 --> 08:14.786
They like to eat the
Kentucky Fried Chicken.

08:14.828 --> 08:16.267
They like to spend a lot

08:16.268 --> 08:17.705
of their time on the internet.

08:17.747 --> 08:21.793
The history of our country
is a history of war.

08:21.835 --> 08:24.421
We had a thousand years
under the Chinese,

08:24.463 --> 08:27.424
and then we had eighty
years under the French,

08:27.466 --> 08:28.716
and then the Japanese came in,

08:28.758 --> 08:32.971
and when the American
left finally in 1975,

08:33.013 --> 08:39.144
we got involved with Cambodia,
so we only have peace

08:39.186 --> 08:41.355
since 1989.

08:41.395 --> 08:43.563
Just in the matter
of a few decades,

08:43.606 --> 08:46.151
the entire population
will be those

08:46.193 --> 08:47.568
without any war experience.

08:47.610 --> 08:49.570
And that's a great thing.

08:49.612 --> 08:51.365
And what are we eating today?

08:51.406 --> 08:52.949
Well, we are going
to have a banh cuon.

08:52.991 --> 08:54.972
- And that means?

08:54.973 --> 08:56.953
- Rice roll, very thin.

08:56.995 --> 08:58.288
- Like a crepe?

08:58.289 --> 08:59.580
- Yes, it's like a crepe.

08:59.622 --> 09:03.584
And inside, ground, minced
pork and wood ear mushroom.

09:03.626 --> 09:05.003
Ah.

09:05.045 --> 09:07.588
♪

09:07.630 --> 09:11.426
And you dip it in,
and there you go.

09:14.637 --> 09:16.431
Mmm.

09:16.473 --> 09:18.266
Oh, that's very good.

09:18.308 --> 09:22.020
Everything we do internationally,
someone refers back

09:22.021 --> 09:23.604
to the Vietnam experience.

09:23.646 --> 09:25.606
You know, "Let's not
do that again," or...

09:25.648 --> 09:27.233
-Let's not repeat Vietnam.

09:27.234 --> 09:30.195
- But I find it interesting
that the people

09:30.237 --> 09:35.033
who had perhaps the
most painful experience

09:35.075 --> 09:38.286
were among the first
to reach out.

09:38.328 --> 09:39.638
- I think the John McCain story...
- Yes.

09:39.662 --> 09:42.623
Is particularly interesting
because here's a guy

09:42.665 --> 09:45.626
who had an atrocious
experience here in prison,

09:45.668 --> 09:49.047
and yet he has been among
the most vocal supporters

09:49.089 --> 09:51.216
of normalizing relations.

09:51.258 --> 09:53.468
It took several
trips to Vietnam,

09:53.510 --> 09:56.263
and so he could see Vietnam
in a different light.

09:56.304 --> 09:58.432
It's no longer a war.

09:58.473 --> 09:59.891
It's a country with people.

09:59.933 --> 10:02.436
Have you been out with
returning veterans from...

10:02.477 --> 10:04.229
Oh, yes, all the time.

10:04.271 --> 10:06.606
Do they often want
to go to the area

10:06.607 --> 10:07.648
that they served?

10:07.690 --> 10:09.650
- Oh, yes.

10:07.690 --> 10:11.236
- Do they often even meet
with the people they fought?

10:11.278 --> 10:12.862
- Yes.

10:12.863 --> 10:14.364
- B-52 pilots come to the areas

10:14.365 --> 10:15.823
they unloaded their bombs?

10:15.865 --> 10:16.824
Yes.

10:16.866 --> 10:19.244
♪

10:19.286 --> 10:20.661
What is that experience like?

10:20.703 --> 10:24.249
What do you see when they come?

10:24.291 --> 10:29.045
Extremely emotional,
extremely emotional.

10:29.087 --> 10:32.507
♪

10:34.593 --> 10:37.262
People burst into tears.

10:37.304 --> 10:42.058
"The memory I kept of you
45 years ago was an enemy."

10:42.100 --> 10:45.479
"I did anything and
everything to protect my life

10:45.520 --> 10:48.689
and to protect the
people in my platoon."

10:49.732 --> 10:52.152
"But today, when I see you again

10:52.193 --> 10:55.280
not as an enemy, as a person."

10:55.322 --> 10:57.698
Everything just disappear.

10:57.740 --> 11:00.827
All the bad feeling
disappear, and now

11:00.828 --> 11:02.078
"Oh, are you married?"

11:02.120 --> 11:03.722
You know, "How many
children do you have?"

11:03.746 --> 11:05.706
You know, "What are you up to?"

11:06.749 --> 11:11.233
Their life turn into a new
chapter, and this chapter

11:11.234 --> 11:12.713
is a good chapter.

11:18.178 --> 11:21.598
[woman speaking
Vietnamese over PA]

11:24.434 --> 11:28.188
Hanoi in the morning, the
usual high-pitched whine

11:28.229 --> 11:29.981
of thousands of motorbikes.

11:31.566 --> 11:34.548
People and the things they
carry coming out to work,

11:34.549 --> 11:37.113
to set up shop, the
sound of commerce...

11:38.781 --> 11:42.681
Of a wildly free market
economy in a system

11:42.682 --> 11:44.579
that's decidedly not.

11:45.955 --> 11:49.459
♪

11:54.255 --> 11:56.966
Ohh!

11:57.008 --> 11:58.759
Hey!

11:58.801 --> 12:00.386
-Whoo!

12:00.387 --> 12:01.971
- Hey! Hey! Hey! Hey!

12:02.013 --> 12:04.328
-Hey! Hey!

12:04.329 --> 12:06.643
- [woman sings in
native language]

12:06.685 --> 12:10.813
When I first came here,
it was Tai Chi at dawn,

12:10.855 --> 12:12.731
and that's still here.

12:14.192 --> 12:15.610
But there's also this.

12:15.652 --> 12:18.154
♪

12:19.822 --> 12:21.032
-Good to see you.

12:21.033 --> 12:22.242
- It's nice to see you too.

12:22.283 --> 12:23.802
- This is An, my friend.
- Nice to meet you.

12:23.826 --> 12:25.786
She's also my Zumba instructor.

12:25.828 --> 12:26.787
Ah.

12:26.829 --> 12:28.747
No Zumba for me.

12:30.291 --> 12:31.834
Breakfast, though, sounds good.

12:31.876 --> 12:33.524
How often a week do you think

12:33.525 --> 12:35.212
the average person
cooks, and how often

12:35.213 --> 12:36.797
do they eat out?

12:36.839 --> 12:38.466
Mostly we just cook
at home for dinner

12:38.508 --> 12:40.385
because that's the
only meal in the day

12:40.427 --> 12:42.429
that everybody can be together.

12:42.470 --> 12:45.848
But for other meals,
normally we eat out.

12:48.851 --> 12:51.854
♪

12:51.896 --> 12:53.814
Whoo!

12:56.651 --> 12:57.985
I meet my old friend Ha

12:58.027 --> 13:00.447
on the edge of the Old
Quarter, a place known

13:00.448 --> 13:01.615
as Cussing Noodles.

13:01.656 --> 13:02.841
This is my favorite,
favorite restaurant.

13:02.865 --> 13:04.618
- This place?
- Yes.

13:04.659 --> 13:06.661
The name comes from
the owner, this lady,

13:06.703 --> 13:10.415
known for the free and
frank way she communicates

13:08.496 --> 13:10.415
with her customers.

13:10.457 --> 13:11.645
-I hear she yells at people.

13:11.646 --> 13:12.833
-Yes.

13:15.295 --> 13:16.837
What are you standing there for?

13:16.879 --> 13:19.466
If you're going to
order, hurry up!

13:19.507 --> 13:21.444
I want the vermicelli with
tongue and ground pork.

13:21.468 --> 13:22.843
I don't have that.

13:22.885 --> 13:24.845
If you like ground
pork go to the market,

13:24.887 --> 13:26.222
they've got lots of it.

13:26.264 --> 13:28.849
If you go to her counter
and order something

13:28.891 --> 13:32.853
and then you indecisive like,
"Oh, can I have these?"

13:32.895 --> 13:35.856
"Oh, no, no, no, no, no,
no, no, maybe I have

13:34.314 --> 13:35.856
these instead,"

13:35.898 --> 13:37.900
she's like, "I don't have
lots of time for you,

13:37.942 --> 13:40.654
so just get out of here."

13:40.695 --> 13:42.447
- Really?
- Yeah.

13:42.489 --> 13:46.451
It's best if you just
go home and eat.

13:46.493 --> 13:48.869
And what's the specialty
of the house here?

13:48.911 --> 13:50.664
"Bun chin zou."

13:50.705 --> 13:51.890
"Chin zou" means pig knuckles.

13:51.914 --> 13:53.458
- Pig knuckle?
- Pig knuckles.

13:53.500 --> 13:54.875
We know that's gonna be good.

13:54.917 --> 13:57.316
You put up with the abuse
for this glorious,

13:57.317 --> 14:00.881
steaming bowl of rice
noodles with spicy chilies,

14:00.923 --> 14:02.487
a rich, hearty, porky broth

14:02.488 --> 14:04.051
with pig's knuckle and snout.

14:04.093 --> 14:06.887
It's the only item on the
menu, and it's good.

14:06.929 --> 14:07.993
- You know taro?

14:07.994 --> 14:09.056
- Yes. Ah.

14:09.098 --> 14:11.559
So this is the stem
- of the taro plant.

14:10.350 --> 14:11.559
- Uh-huh.

14:11.601 --> 14:14.312
And to prepare this, you
have to be very careful

14:14.354 --> 14:15.896
because if you
don't do it right,

14:15.938 --> 14:17.691
- then you get itchy mouth.
- Toxic, right.

14:17.732 --> 14:18.899
No, no, not toxic.

14:18.941 --> 14:20.568
- You won't die from it but...
- Right.

14:20.610 --> 14:22.903
It makes your mouth
really itchy, so...

14:22.945 --> 14:24.155
Interesting.

14:24.197 --> 14:27.617
♪

14:28.951 --> 14:29.910
Mmm.

14:29.952 --> 14:31.912
Wow, that's delicious.

14:31.954 --> 14:33.516
When people talk about
Vietnam, they always say

14:33.540 --> 14:37.126
about spring rolls or pho,
but I think this should be

14:37.127 --> 14:38.294
in... in the mix.

14:38.336 --> 14:39.920
- In the mix?

14:39.921 --> 14:42.089
- Yeah, in... I'm easy.

14:42.090 --> 14:44.801
Give me some spicy
noodles, some pork,

14:42.131 --> 14:44.801
I'm happy every time.

14:44.843 --> 14:46.886
Get out of here.

14:47.970 --> 14:51.599
♪

14:54.853 --> 14:55.936
Hello.

14:58.022 --> 15:00.983
♪

15:28.010 --> 15:30.971
♪

15:33.015 --> 15:35.602
It's a maze of narrow
streets and alleyways

15:35.643 --> 15:38.187
behind the old French cathedral.

15:38.229 --> 15:42.191
♪

15:44.402 --> 15:48.448
Vendors set up stools, and
it's happy hour in Hanoi.

15:58.416 --> 16:01.628
♪

16:02.712 --> 16:07.007
Every doorway, every window,
a little slice of life.

16:07.049 --> 16:10.010
♪

16:16.434 --> 16:18.018
A story all its own.

16:18.060 --> 16:22.064
Lives lived, being lived,
caught for a second,

16:22.106 --> 16:25.067
a moment, then gone.

16:27.528 --> 16:30.615
In Vietnam sometime,
to be truly friend,

16:30.657 --> 16:32.826
- to be friendly...
- Yeah.

16:32.867 --> 16:35.035
We have to drink
until we a drunk.

16:35.077 --> 16:36.203
Well, well, okay.

16:36.245 --> 16:37.663
- Yeah.

16:37.664 --> 16:39.081
-We must. We must.

16:40.500 --> 16:42.877
Cheer for friendship.

16:42.919 --> 16:45.463
Linh Dinh, my oldest
friend in Vietnam

16:45.505 --> 16:46.673
from the very beginning.

16:46.714 --> 16:48.424
Many happy memories, my friend.

16:48.466 --> 16:52.052
We've been to Saigon,
Can Tho, Nha Trang.

16:52.094 --> 16:54.681
He was my original minder
for Vietnam's Ministry

16:54.722 --> 16:56.432
of Foreign Affairs.

16:56.474 --> 16:58.893
We became, in spite of his
official responsibilities,

16:58.935 --> 16:59.998
-fast friends.

16:59.999 --> 17:01.061
- One, two, three.

17:03.356 --> 17:04.315
- Welcome back.
- Welcome back.

17:04.357 --> 17:05.858
- Cheers.
- Thank you.

17:05.900 --> 17:07.652
Linh has brought me
to a great and proud

17:07.694 --> 17:10.696
and uniquely Hanoi
tradition, Bia Hai.

17:10.738 --> 17:12.656
Bia Hai refers to
the roadside joints

17:12.699 --> 17:15.492
where locals gather to
consume keg-dispensed,

17:15.535 --> 17:17.871
freshly brewed draft beer.

17:17.912 --> 17:19.705
Oh, that's good.

17:19.747 --> 17:21.080
It's not strong at
all, my friend.

17:21.123 --> 17:23.751
Just, like, between
three to four percent.

17:23.792 --> 17:25.461
Ah, so we need to drink a lot.

17:25.502 --> 17:26.671
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

17:26.713 --> 17:27.964
Cheer for Hanoi beer.

17:31.926 --> 17:34.094
♪

17:34.136 --> 17:36.305
It was something
luxurious 30 years ago.

17:36.347 --> 17:37.724
- Yeah.
- Right.

17:37.765 --> 17:39.117
- And now it's for everyone.
- Yeah.

17:39.141 --> 17:40.894
- It's not expensive.
- Right.

17:40.935 --> 17:42.687
- Ten thousand dong.

17:42.688 --> 17:44.522
- So that's...
- Forty cents.

17:42.729 --> 17:44.522
- Forty, forty-five cents, yeah.

17:44.564 --> 17:46.106
- Forty-five cents a beer?
- Yeah.

17:46.148 --> 17:47.483
I'll have another.

17:47.525 --> 17:49.109
I can afford that.

17:49.151 --> 17:52.739
♪

17:52.780 --> 17:54.532
The country's changed so much.

17:54.574 --> 17:57.493
When I first came,
bicycles and motorbikes.

17:57.535 --> 17:58.557
-Now, lot of cars.

17:58.558 --> 17:59.579
- More cars.

17:59.620 --> 18:01.121
Yeah, now look, money.

18:01.163 --> 18:02.725
People are making
mo... business is good.

18:02.749 --> 18:04.166
- Yeah.
- Right?

18:04.208 --> 18:05.919
I mean, much, much,
much more tourism

18:05.960 --> 18:07.712
- every year, yeah?
- Yes, yes.

18:07.754 --> 18:11.131
People also enjoy life more.

18:11.173 --> 18:14.343
♪

18:41.829 --> 18:44.999
♪

19:19.450 --> 19:22.996
Search the globe, and you
will find no other place

19:23.037 --> 19:26.415
that looks remotely like this.

19:26.457 --> 19:29.836
♪

19:38.511 --> 19:41.576
"Ha Long" means "where
the dragon descends

19:41.577 --> 19:43.223
into the sea".

19:43.265 --> 19:44.976
And legend says that this is

19:44.977 --> 19:48.312
where a great dragon
charged, protecting Vietnam

19:48.313 --> 19:49.897
from foreign invaders.

19:49.939 --> 19:53.233
War is a constant theme
in Vietnamese mythology

19:53.275 --> 19:55.235
and history.

19:55.277 --> 19:58.447
The Chinese, the French, the
Japanese, the Americans,

19:58.489 --> 20:01.408
the Cambodians,
again the Chinese.

20:01.450 --> 20:04.871
♪

20:28.936 --> 20:30.730
♪

20:30.771 --> 20:33.315
Ha Long Bay has become,
for better or worse,

20:33.357 --> 20:36.069
one of Vietnam's most
visited destinations.

20:36.110 --> 20:38.196
♪

20:40.322 --> 20:42.282
Fortunately, this
time of year anyway,

20:42.324 --> 20:44.014
you don't have to go too far

20:44.015 --> 20:47.287
to lose yourself in the
past, find a quiet place

20:47.329 --> 20:50.290
where you can still imagine
the great dragon's

20:50.291 --> 20:52.251
tail thrashing and
churning and kicking up

20:52.252 --> 20:54.170
these great karsts of rock.

20:54.212 --> 20:56.338
♪

20:58.716 --> 21:01.719
Chosen mode of transportation,
the "Emeraude,"

21:01.761 --> 21:05.180
an old French-era steamer
refitted for more

21:05.181 --> 21:08.184
current-day needs.

21:08.226 --> 21:11.520
♪

21:11.562 --> 21:14.732
A big freaking boat.

21:14.774 --> 21:18.318
♪

21:18.360 --> 21:20.196
And it's all mine.

21:22.573 --> 21:24.992
Along with friends
and crew, of course.

21:45.763 --> 21:48.182
♪

22:09.411 --> 22:10.537
I like this boat.

22:10.579 --> 22:11.974
We're living a little
larger than last...

22:11.998 --> 22:15.375
Last time the boat
was not this nice.

22:15.417 --> 22:17.190
All the modern conveniences

22:17.191 --> 22:18.963
but the charms of the past.

22:19.005 --> 22:22.549
It fits perfectly with my
over-romantic delusions.

22:22.591 --> 22:26.179
And in general,
it does not suck.

22:31.642 --> 22:33.019
Hello, gentlemen.

22:33.060 --> 22:34.603
- Hi, Tony.
- How you doing?

22:34.645 --> 22:36.396
We've having some gin and tonic.

22:36.438 --> 22:39.275
Gin and tonic, traditional
Vietnamese drink.

22:39.317 --> 22:40.860
Well, not really,
but... all right.

22:40.901 --> 22:42.569
This my first time trying this.

22:42.611 --> 22:43.779
- Yeah?
- His first time.

22:43.821 --> 22:45.405
How old are you anyway?

22:43.821 --> 22:46.782
Wait a minute, you were
five years old last time

22:46.824 --> 22:47.867
I was in Ha Long Bay.

22:47.908 --> 22:49.389
-Yeah, just five. He 20 now.

22:49.390 --> 22:50.870
-Wow.

22:50.911 --> 22:53.330
Linh and I came here for
another show what feels like

22:53.331 --> 22:55.208
a lifetime ago.

22:55.249 --> 22:57.417
Back then, I got to
meet his son Minh,

22:57.459 --> 22:59.419
who's apparently grown up.

22:59.461 --> 23:01.588
These are pictures
of you and him.

23:01.630 --> 23:04.424
- Whoa.
- Fifteen years ago, fourteen years ago.

23:04.466 --> 23:06.426
Oh, my God.

23:06.468 --> 23:08.304
Look at my hair.

23:08.346 --> 23:10.430
♪

23:10.472 --> 23:11.682
It's changed a little bit.

23:11.724 --> 23:13.642
Like over eight million people

23:13.684 --> 23:15.102
are coming to Ha Long Bay now?

23:15.144 --> 23:17.604
Yeah, every year, tourists.

23:20.482 --> 23:21.710
All of this is protected, right?

23:21.734 --> 23:23.819
You can't do anything
on these rocks.

23:23.861 --> 23:25.112
- No.
- No, no.

23:25.154 --> 23:28.448
And how many of these
islands... is it 1,900

23:26.488 --> 23:28.448
of these rocks out there?

23:28.490 --> 23:30.910
One thousand nine
hundred and sixty-nine,

23:30.951 --> 23:33.246
and this is a good
number, you know?

23:33.287 --> 23:34.455
It's a lucky number?

23:34.456 --> 23:35.622
- Six is for fortune.

23:35.664 --> 23:37.457
- Right.

23:35.664 --> 23:39.043
- And nine is for forever,
so fortune forever.

23:39.085 --> 23:40.502
♪

23:40.544 --> 23:44.464
A drink or two on the
top deck, check.

23:44.506 --> 23:47.509
Now for the rest of
the day trying to do

23:47.510 --> 23:49.469
as little as possible.

23:49.511 --> 23:55.142
A nap, sunset, maybe
some more drinks,

23:55.184 --> 23:57.895
and what about dinner?

23:57.937 --> 23:59.001
- One for you.

23:59.002 --> 24:00.064
- Oh, thank you, sir.

24:00.106 --> 24:01.628
- Cheer, my friend.

24:01.629 --> 24:03.150
- Cheers.

24:03.192 --> 24:04.944
So we're eating some squid?

24:04.985 --> 24:06.236
- Tons of squid.

24:06.237 --> 24:07.487
-Tons of squid?

24:07.529 --> 24:11.491
We try to get as many
tons as possible.

24:11.533 --> 24:13.786
Cue the majesty of the squid.

24:17.331 --> 24:19.125
At night this time of
year, the bright lights

24:19.166 --> 24:21.919
of Ha Long Bay's fishing
boats are unmistakable.

24:21.961 --> 24:24.504
They can only catch the
squid in the evening.

24:24.546 --> 24:27.029
The light attract the squid
- so they can catch them.

24:27.030 --> 24:28.092
- Right.

24:28.134 --> 24:30.136
They say that because
of global warming,

24:30.177 --> 24:32.679
all the fish are dying
but that the squid

24:32.721 --> 24:34.890
and cuttlefish populations
are increasing,

24:34.932 --> 24:36.725
so soon the whole sea will be

24:36.726 --> 24:38.518
filled with plenty of squid.

24:38.560 --> 24:39.937
We'll be eating it every day.

24:39.979 --> 24:43.190
♪

24:48.988 --> 24:51.949
Oh, yeah, those are
cute, little squid.

24:51.991 --> 24:54.160
Oh, those are gonna be tender.

24:54.201 --> 24:55.911
- Ooh.
- Mmm.

24:55.953 --> 24:58.414
Oh, yeah, the tentacles
are the best.

24:58.456 --> 25:00.333
To catch squid is
a very hard job.

25:00.374 --> 25:01.458
- They work all the night.

25:01.459 --> 25:02.542
- All the night.

25:02.584 --> 25:05.144
- They work all the night.
- The light, it turn on all the night.

25:05.171 --> 25:07.214
Right, and then sleep all day?

25:07.256 --> 25:09.425
- Yeah.
- It's got to be hot out there, man,

25:09.467 --> 25:10.759
- sleeping in the day.
- Yeah.

25:10.801 --> 25:11.865
-Cheer for the day.

25:11.866 --> 25:12.928
- Cheers for the day.

25:12.970 --> 25:16.182
♪

25:18.767 --> 25:21.979
♪

25:59.058 --> 26:00.434
♪

26:00.476 --> 26:06.190
A morning swim, a bowl of
spicy noodles, and a view,

26:06.232 --> 26:07.191
perfect.

26:07.233 --> 26:10.568
♪

26:19.495 --> 26:20.787
How many in the family?

26:20.829 --> 26:23.623
Six. Young couple and
their three kids

26:23.665 --> 26:26.210
and then the grandma
is living with them.

26:26.252 --> 26:27.420
The oldest kid is a girl,

26:27.461 --> 26:29.650
and she was sent into the
shore with some relatives

26:29.651 --> 26:31.966
to go to school -because
they have no schooling here.

26:31.967 --> 26:33.259
-Right.

26:33.300 --> 26:34.843
♪

26:34.885 --> 26:38.055
Floating fishing villages
like this used to be found

26:38.056 --> 26:39.432
in nearly every sheltered cove

26:39.473 --> 26:41.641
or corner of Ha Long Bay.

26:41.683 --> 26:43.164
But as Vietnam becomes a more

26:43.165 --> 26:44.644
popular tourist destination,

26:44.686 --> 26:48.482
authentic fishing villages
are starting to disappear.

26:48.524 --> 26:49.709
The government has
been relocating

26:49.733 --> 26:53.570
fishing families inland,
hoping to minimize

26:53.571 --> 26:55.655
their ecological impact.

26:55.697 --> 26:58.451
The people living on
floating villages,

26:58.492 --> 27:00.974
they're just generally
nice and willing to open

27:00.975 --> 27:03.685
their home to us and... -
They basically farm oysters?

27:03.686 --> 27:05.082
-Yeah, yeah.

27:05.124 --> 27:06.896
A lot of pearls for
sale in Ha Long Bay

27:06.897 --> 27:08.668
and in Vietnam.

27:08.710 --> 27:11.547
They come from places like this.

27:11.589 --> 27:12.923
♪

27:12.965 --> 27:15.675
It takes over a year
to grow each pearl,

27:15.717 --> 27:17.490
and there's no guarantee

27:17.491 --> 27:19.263
an oyster will even yield one.

27:19.305 --> 27:22.640
♪

27:24.560 --> 27:26.479
Water spinach, I think
that's called, right?

27:26.520 --> 27:27.896
Water spinach.

27:27.938 --> 27:29.940
♪

27:29.982 --> 27:31.942
That's the most common
vegetable for Vietnamese

27:31.984 --> 27:33.360
- in the summertime.
- Yes.

27:33.402 --> 27:34.736
- Mm-hmm.
- Yeah.

27:34.778 --> 27:36.947
♪

27:36.989 --> 27:38.949
What kind of fish are these?

27:40.784 --> 27:42.432
-Little fish?

27:42.433 --> 27:44.079
-Yeah, Ha Long fish.

27:44.121 --> 27:45.310
- Ha Long fish.

27:45.311 --> 27:46.499
- Yeah.

27:46.540 --> 27:48.584
♪

27:48.626 --> 27:49.960
It's delicious, yeah.

27:50.002 --> 27:51.962
- It's good fish.
- Mmm.

27:52.004 --> 27:55.549
This is a pretty prime
piece of real estate,

27:55.591 --> 27:56.734
and they've lived here how long?

27:56.758 --> 27:57.968
For many generations.

27:58.010 --> 28:01.451
This old grandma is 78 years
old, and she said that

28:01.452 --> 28:02.889
her grandparents lived here

28:02.931 --> 28:04.829
before this all become, like,

28:04.830 --> 28:06.726
a big tourist attraction.

28:06.768 --> 28:09.938
Is their situation
protected by the state?

28:09.980 --> 28:11.773
They're allowed to
live here by special...

28:11.815 --> 28:12.917
Because they've
been here so long?

28:12.941 --> 28:16.903
Actually, the government
now is encouraging them

28:16.904 --> 28:19.906
to move back to shore
because it's better

28:16.945 --> 28:19.906
for their children's education.

28:19.948 --> 28:23.743
To tell the truth, we would
like to move on land.

28:23.785 --> 28:26.413
If the government did
offer us anything,

28:26.455 --> 28:29.124
then we should take it.

28:29.166 --> 28:33.962
But right now we would
need help to live ashore.

28:34.004 --> 28:36.756
For someone like me
who isn't educated

28:36.757 --> 28:38.758
and got skilled in the
kind of work on land...

28:38.800 --> 28:40.969
I'm just used to working
on the ocean, fishing...

28:41.011 --> 28:43.993
They said that they're happy
to move back because it's

28:43.994 --> 28:45.182
better for their children,

28:45.224 --> 28:47.601
but they've been living
here for many centuries,

28:47.643 --> 28:49.562
and all they know
is just fishing.

28:49.603 --> 28:50.604
Right.

28:54.858 --> 28:58.028
♪

29:12.834 --> 29:16.380
Just another day in paradise.

29:16.422 --> 29:19.592
A tropical downpour in a
working class neighborhood

29:19.633 --> 29:21.677
on the outskirts of Hanoi.

29:21.719 --> 29:24.846
♪

29:26.098 --> 29:29.184
The lady selling vegetables
and gum and cigarettes

29:29.226 --> 29:32.605
taking a nap under a
piece of corrugated tin

29:32.646 --> 29:35.815
has no idea what's
about to happen.

29:35.857 --> 29:37.234
Turn around for me, sir.

29:43.657 --> 29:44.491
Thank you.

29:44.533 --> 29:46.993
♪

29:47.035 --> 29:50.247
♪

29:54.293 --> 29:57.671
♪ Paid the cost to be the boss ♪

29:59.256 --> 30:04.219
♪ Look at me ♪ You
know what you see

30:04.261 --> 30:06.221
♪ You see a bad mutha

30:08.890 --> 30:13.853
♪ Look at me ♪ You
know what you see

30:13.895 --> 30:17.774
♪ You see a bad mutha -Mr.
President.

30:17.775 --> 30:19.025
-Good to see you.

30:19.067 --> 30:20.653
Good to see you.

30:20.694 --> 30:22.446
Mr. President, how are
you liking Vietnam?

30:22.488 --> 30:23.739
Love it.

30:23.781 --> 30:26.325
Markets like these
I grew up with.

30:26.366 --> 30:29.307
When I was a kid in Jakarta,
these were basically

30:29.308 --> 30:30.663
the only markets available.

30:30.704 --> 30:32.872
You know, you would buy
pretty much everything

30:32.914 --> 30:34.667
in stalls like this.

30:34.708 --> 30:35.893
Yeah, I wouldn't
mind going in there

30:35.917 --> 30:38.878
and haggling and seeing
what I could find.

30:38.920 --> 30:40.880
This country, when I
first arrived here,

30:40.922 --> 30:43.883
it smelled like a place
that I would like.

30:43.925 --> 30:46.345
Certain countries
just... pheromonically,

30:46.386 --> 30:48.888
- they just smell good, and I know they're
- gonna be good.

30:48.930 --> 30:50.890
Do you... do you kind
of smell that?

30:50.932 --> 30:53.435
You know, there's certain
spices that you can smell

30:53.436 --> 30:55.854
in certain countries
that you just don't

30:55.855 --> 30:56.896
smell back home.

30:56.938 --> 31:00.025
Now, you know, there are
some smells that aren't

31:00.026 --> 31:02.361
as appealing as well, but
that's part of the mix.

31:02.402 --> 31:04.070
- It is indeed.
- So, yeah.

31:04.112 --> 31:05.739
♪

31:05.781 --> 31:09.075
♪ Head for the turnaround
How you doing, guys?

31:09.117 --> 31:10.577
How are you?

31:10.619 --> 31:12.746
♪ Heading for the turnaround

31:15.541 --> 31:17.292
I love you, Obama!

31:17.334 --> 31:20.754
♪

31:27.135 --> 31:30.347
♪

31:35.977 --> 31:39.815
There's something magical
about the smell.

31:39.857 --> 31:41.941
The minute you touch down here,

31:41.983 --> 31:45.362
it grabs you, captivates
you, and chances are,

31:45.363 --> 31:46.946
it holds you forever.

31:46.988 --> 31:49.991
I'm not the first
to feel this way.

31:58.458 --> 32:01.628
There is no better place
to entertain the leader

32:01.629 --> 32:03.963
of the free world,
in my opinion,

32:01.670 --> 32:03.963
than one of these classic,

32:04.005 --> 32:05.883
funky, family-run noodle shops

32:05.884 --> 32:07.760
you find all over Hanoi.

32:07.801 --> 32:10.970
Dinner and a beer cost
about six dollars.

32:11.012 --> 32:12.972
I'm guessing the President
doesn't get a lot

32:13.014 --> 32:15.768
of state dinners like this.

32:15.809 --> 32:18.937
♪

32:21.815 --> 32:24.777
How often do you get to
sneak out for a beer?

32:24.818 --> 32:26.152
Very rarely.

32:26.194 --> 32:29.197
First of all, I don't get
to sneak out, period.

32:29.239 --> 32:33.034
But the... once in a while,
I'll take Michelle out

32:33.035 --> 32:34.035
on a date night.

32:34.077 --> 32:36.996
The problem is part of
enjoying a restaurant

32:37.038 --> 32:38.998
is sitting with other patrons

32:39.040 --> 32:42.211
and enjoying the
atmosphere, and too often

32:42.212 --> 32:43.587
we end up getting shunted

32:43.629 --> 32:45.631
into one of those private
rooms in the back.

32:45.672 --> 32:47.006
Well, I'm glad I could help,

32:47.048 --> 32:48.610
and to many more cold beers, Mr.
President.

32:48.634 --> 32:50.009
I appreciate it, absolutely.

32:52.053 --> 32:53.179
Mmm.

32:53.221 --> 32:56.308
♪

33:01.855 --> 33:04.065
All right, you're gonna
have to... I will walk you

33:02.856 --> 33:04.065
through it.

33:04.107 --> 33:05.668
You're gonna have to
walk me through this.

33:05.692 --> 33:09.613
We're about to eat bun cha... ♪

33:09.655 --> 33:13.388
And it is about as typical
and uniquely a Hanoi dish

33:13.389 --> 33:14.910
as there is.

33:14.952 --> 33:17.078
These beautiful
little pork patties,

33:17.120 --> 33:19.038
some grilled pork belly.

33:19.080 --> 33:22.208
Bun cha is served in a
broth of vinegar, sugar,

33:22.250 --> 33:25.670
and the ubiquitous nuoc
mam, or Vietnamese

33:25.671 --> 33:27.255
fermented fish sauce.

33:27.297 --> 33:29.424
Chilies to taste.

33:29.466 --> 33:31.510
I mean, if you have
an important state

33:31.511 --> 33:33.219
function after, you
might not want

33:31.551 --> 33:33.219
to go too heavy on it.

33:33.261 --> 33:35.221
- You know what?
- I'm going with this thing.

33:35.263 --> 33:38.057
You know, we're gonna
do what's appropriate.

33:38.099 --> 33:39.935
- Vinegar.
- All right.

33:39.977 --> 33:41.854
And then you just
hack off noodles,

33:41.895 --> 33:44.063
and just drop them
into your bowl.

33:44.105 --> 33:47.066
Yeah, it's not too
elegant, but I'm managing.

33:47.108 --> 33:49.903
And you dip and
stir and get ready

33:49.904 --> 33:50.904
for the awesomeness.

33:50.946 --> 33:52.071
I'm ready.

33:52.113 --> 33:54.073
Now, is it appropriate
to just pop

33:54.115 --> 33:55.677
one of these whole
suckers in your mouth?

33:55.701 --> 33:57.744
Or do you think that you
should be a little more...

33:57.786 --> 33:59.913
Well, slurping is
totally acceptable

33:59.955 --> 34:02.081
- in this part of the world.
- Oh, is it?

34:02.123 --> 34:03.917
It takes some
skills, by the way,

34:03.959 --> 34:06.085
to handle these
sticky, cold noodles.

34:06.127 --> 34:10.089
But whatever your opinion
of the man, the President

34:10.090 --> 34:11.320
has those skills... -Mmm.

34:11.321 --> 34:12.509
- I got to say.

34:12.551 --> 34:14.110
- This is killer.
- This is outstanding.

34:14.135 --> 34:15.697
- That's so good to hear.
- It's really good.

34:15.721 --> 34:18.911
And we share, apparently,
a sentimentality

34:18.911 --> 34:22.268
about Asian street food and
Southeast Asia in general.

34:22.310 --> 34:26.356
One of my favorite meals of
all time, there's an area

34:26.398 --> 34:30.547
between Jakarta and Bandung,
another city in Indonesia

34:30.549 --> 34:33.780
called Puncak, and it's
up through the mountains.

34:33.822 --> 34:36.282
So you'd have these
roadside restaurants

34:36.324 --> 34:39.284
overlooking the tea fields.

34:39.327 --> 34:40.913
There'd be a river running

34:40.954 --> 34:43.121
through the restaurant itself,

34:40.954 --> 34:43.956
and there'd be these fish,
these carp that would be

34:43.958 --> 34:46.001
running through, and
you'd pick the fish.

34:46.043 --> 34:48.670
They'd grab it for you and
fry it up, and the skin

34:48.670 --> 34:51.590
would be real crispy,
and they just served it

34:51.591 --> 34:54.009
with a bed of rice, and it was

34:54.010 --> 34:55.677
the simplest meal
possible, and nothing

34:55.678 --> 34:57.303
tasted so good.

34:57.345 --> 34:59.014
♪

34:59.056 --> 35:01.516
Now, as a Chicagoan...
Trickier question

35:01.558 --> 35:03.602
fraught with peril.

35:03.643 --> 35:06.021
Is ketchup on a hot
dog ever acceptable?

35:06.063 --> 35:07.188
No.

35:07.230 --> 35:08.314
No, I re... I mean that.

35:08.356 --> 35:09.942
That's one of those
things like...

35:09.983 --> 35:11.150
Well, let me put it this way.

35:11.192 --> 35:13.028
It's not acceptable
past the age of eight.

35:13.070 --> 35:15.530
My daughter's eight, and
she put ketchup on eggs

35:15.572 --> 35:18.408
the other day, and I... I
wi... I didn't know

35:18.409 --> 35:21.160
what the good...
What good parenting

35:18.450 --> 35:21.160
called for at this point.

35:21.202 --> 35:23.162
- An intervention.
- I think so.

35:23.204 --> 35:25.040
I think you just got to
say, "You know what?

35:25.082 --> 35:26.124
That's not acceptable.

35:26.125 --> 35:27.166
I'm sorry."

35:27.208 --> 35:30.128
♪

35:35.884 --> 35:39.178
We are at a point where we
seem to be turning inwards.

35:39.220 --> 35:42.433
I mean, we're actually talking
about building a wall

35:42.434 --> 35:43.767
around our country.

35:43.809 --> 35:46.645
And yet you have been
reaching out to people

35:46.686 --> 35:48.563
who don't necessarily
agree with us...

35:48.605 --> 35:52.025
Gaza, Iran, Cuba.

35:52.067 --> 35:55.194
- I mean, I just wish that more Americans
- had passports.

35:55.236 --> 35:58.031
The extent of what you can
see how other people live

35:58.073 --> 36:01.639
seems useful at worst and
incredibly pleasurable

36:01.640 --> 36:03.202
and interesting at best.

36:03.244 --> 36:07.019
It confirms the basic truth
that people everywhere

36:07.020 --> 36:10.627
are pretty much the same,
the same hopes and dreams,

36:10.669 --> 36:12.378
and when you come to
a place like Vietnam

36:12.420 --> 36:16.382
and you see former American
Vietnam vets coming back,

36:16.424 --> 36:17.905
when you see somebody like

36:17.906 --> 36:19.385
a John Kerry or a John McCain,

36:19.427 --> 36:21.242
two very different people

36:21.243 --> 36:23.056
politically and temperamentally,

36:23.098 --> 36:26.852
but who were able to
bond in their experience

36:26.893 --> 36:29.228
of meeting with their
former adversaries

36:29.270 --> 36:32.398
and you don't make peace
with your friends.

36:32.440 --> 36:34.233
You make peace
with your enemies.

36:34.275 --> 36:37.696
♪

36:39.447 --> 36:43.242
As a father of a young girl,
is it all gonna be okay?

36:43.284 --> 36:44.911
It's all gonna work out?

36:44.912 --> 36:46.830
My daughter will be
able to come here

36:44.953 --> 36:46.830
in five years, ten years?

36:46.872 --> 36:48.832
She'll be able to have
a bowl of bun cha,

36:48.874 --> 36:50.917
and the world will
be a better place?

36:50.959 --> 36:52.836
Yeah.

36:50.959 --> 36:54.504
I mean, I think progress
is not a straight line.

36:54.546 --> 36:56.089
You know, there are
gonna be moments

36:56.131 --> 37:00.281
at any given part of
the world where things

37:00.282 --> 37:02.428
are terrible.

37:02.470 --> 37:05.891
But having said all that...

37:06.975 --> 37:10.269
I think things are
gonna work out.

37:10.311 --> 37:12.064
- Thank you so much.
- Cheers.

37:12.105 --> 37:13.272
Cheers.

37:14.691 --> 37:18.945
[woman sings a cappella
in native language]

37:29.122 --> 37:31.958
♪

37:32.000 --> 37:34.502
The vast majority
of this country

37:34.544 --> 37:36.088
don't remember the American War.

37:36.129 --> 37:37.527
-They don't remember any war.

37:37.528 --> 37:38.924
-No.

37:38.965 --> 37:40.508
You used to be a tour guide?

37:40.550 --> 37:41.614
-Yes.

37:41.615 --> 37:42.677
- For how many years?

37:42.719 --> 37:43.825
-Fifteen years.

37:43.826 --> 37:44.930
- Fifteen years?

37:44.971 --> 37:47.891
I know you have to bring
people over to the museum,

37:47.933 --> 37:50.351
the American War museum,
what, every time, right?

37:50.393 --> 37:51.811
Yup.

37:54.522 --> 37:57.316
In your lifetime, is
there gonna be a time

37:57.358 --> 38:00.319
when that's not gonna
have to be a stop?

38:00.361 --> 38:02.572
It won't be necessary, it
won't even be important,

38:02.614 --> 38:03.907
no one will remember?

38:03.949 --> 38:05.324
Or should people
always remember?

38:05.366 --> 38:08.391
I think it's good to
remember so we don't make

38:08.392 --> 38:09.537
the same mistake, you know?

38:09.579 --> 38:12.958
Some people choose to be
angry, to hold grudge.

38:12.999 --> 38:15.376
But then some people
chose to let go

38:15.418 --> 38:18.713
and... for the peace
inside themself.

38:18.755 --> 38:21.549
That's up to the person.

38:21.591 --> 38:24.302
And I think it's good that...

38:30.391 --> 38:34.062
It's important that we
know about history.

38:39.067 --> 38:41.861
And to make sure it's
never happen again.

38:52.580 --> 38:57.169
I met a lot of war veterans,
and surprisingly,

38:57.210 --> 39:00.421
a lot of them don't feel...
Don't have any anger

39:00.463 --> 39:07.095
against their old enemies... ♪

39:11.099 --> 39:13.643
And that's... that's amazing.

39:13.685 --> 39:15.603
That's... that is amazing.

39:15.645 --> 39:18.397
I learned so much from them.

39:18.439 --> 39:21.693
♪

39:33.830 --> 39:37.125
♪

39:40.461 --> 39:44.049
For Vietnamese, we
have so many legends.

39:44.090 --> 39:46.634
But the majority of legends
related to our tradition

39:46.676 --> 39:49.428
- of fighting against foreign invaders...
- Uh-hmm.

39:49.470 --> 39:51.430
And to protect our country.

39:51.472 --> 39:54.726
♪

39:58.479 --> 40:01.024
Over the last 20
years of my life,

40:01.066 --> 40:04.277
I've seen a lot of changes.

40:04.319 --> 40:07.446
And we know that there's still
a lot of shortcoming...

40:08.698 --> 40:12.118
♪

40:14.287 --> 40:16.039
But everything needs time.

40:16.081 --> 40:17.332
We need to be patient.

40:17.374 --> 40:20.022
We can't rush because
we really don't want

40:20.023 --> 40:21.294
another war.

40:24.881 --> 40:27.988
General William Westmoreland,
who commanded US forces

40:27.989 --> 40:30.929
here in the mid-'60s,
famously said,

40:30.970 --> 40:34.891
"The Oriental doesn't put
the same high price on life

40:34.933 --> 40:36.851
as does a Westerner.

40:36.893 --> 40:38.477
Life is plentiful.

40:38.519 --> 40:41.273
Life is cheap in the Orient."

40:41.314 --> 40:44.067
♪

40:44.109 --> 40:46.485
It was an extraordinarily
grotesque

40:46.527 --> 40:49.135
and wrongheaded
observation from a guy

40:49.136 --> 40:52.012
who, if nothing else, was
expected to understand

40:52.013 --> 40:53.868
his enemy on the battlefield.

40:53.910 --> 40:57.496
He could not, it turned
out, do even that.

40:57.538 --> 41:00.750
♪

41:04.129 --> 41:08.507
Maybe, I hope, we are a
little bit smarter now.

41:08.549 --> 41:10.509
♪

